<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n32058d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n32" href="#n32058d">N32 (VI.B.23)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n32all.htm#n32058d"> 58(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> appel / karma</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> English has contributed <font color="green">[to H.]</font> a number of words, some of which have even found a place in the literature of the language; <i>e.g. kamishanar</i> (commissioner); <i>jaj</i> (judge), <i>daktar</i> (doctor); <i>daktari</i>, &ldquo;the science of medicinne&rdquo; or &ldquo;the profession of physicians&rdquo;; &hellip; <i>sosayati</i> (society), <i>apil</i> (appeal); <mark><i>apil karna</i>, &ldquo;to appeal&rdquo;</mark>; &hellip; <i>inc</i> (inch); <i>fut</i> (foot); and many more, are now words commonly used. Some borrowed words are distorted into the shape of genuine Hindostani words familair to the speakers; <i>e.g.</i> the English railway term &ldquo;signal&rdquo; has become <i>sikandar</i>, the native name for Alexander the Great, and &ldquo;signal-man&rdquo; is <i>sikandar-man</i>, or &ldquo;the priest of Alexander.&rdquo; <small> &ldquo;HINDOSTANI&rdquo; <a name="EBHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBHI"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 480(b) [Hindostani as a Lingua Franca]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
